Of the 202 sputum samples tested, 67 reacted with both MN Genus-specific and MTBC-specific probes, none reacted only with the MTBC-specific probe, and 22 reacted only with the MN Genus-specific probe. The FISH assay yielded results in 2h and had a limit of detection of 2.2×104CFU/ml in sputum spiked with cultured M. tuberculosis. The diagnostic sensitivity, specificity, and positive and negative predictive values of the FISH assay for MTBC in patient sputa were 89.7%, 95.5%, 88.0%, and 92.6%, respectively. NTM were a significant cause of tuberculosis-like infections in Mangaluru.
